Autonomy, Shell, Barclays, SABMiller: U.K., Irish Equity Preview

-- B y   B l a n c h e   G a t t   a n d   A d r i a   C i m i n o
-- 
2011-08-22T06:41:34Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-21/autonomy-corp-barclays-sabmiller-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
that may have unusual share-price changes in U.K. and Irish
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are from
the last market close.  September futures on the FTSE 100 Index lost 1.1 percent to
4,980.5 at 7:39 a.m. in  London . The FTSE 100 fell 51.47 points,
or 1 percent, to 5,040.76 on Aug. 19. The FTSE All-Share Index
dropped 1 percent, while Ireland’s ISEQ Index retreated 1.4
percent.  Amlin Plc (AML)  : The biggest Lloyd’s of London insurer
by market value swung to a loss in the first half after record
claims from natural disasters in  Japan ,  New Zealand  and
Australia. The net loss was 151.7 million pounds ($250 million).
The stock slipped 0.7 percent to 322.8 pence.  Autonomy Corp. (AU/ LN): Mike Lynch, Chief Executive
Officer of the U.K. software maker being bought by Hewlett-
Packard Co., said U.S. and U.K. companies should operate on a
“level playing field” concerning takeovers, the Sunday
Telegraph reported. The shares jumped 72 percent to 2,452 pence.  BAE Systems Plc (BA/)  : The U.K. arms company may lose an
$850 million contract to operate an ammunition plant in Virginia
after the U.S. Army said it would reconsider proposals for the
work. The stock declined 0.1 percent to 253.5 pence.  Barclays Plc (BARC)  : The U.K.’s second-largest lender by
assets and Johannesburg-based Impala Platinum Holdings Ltd. said
they’ve received letters from Zimbabwe’s government regarding
submissions made to meet a requirement to sell half their local
units to black Zimbabweans. The stock dropped 2.3 percent to
150.5 pence.  Cairn Energy Plc (CNE)  : The Scottish oil and gas
producer may bid for offshore exploration licenses in Lebanon
that the Middle Eastern country’s government plans to auction
before the end of the year, the Sunday Times reported, without
citing anyone. The shares retreated 1.8 percent to 281.4 pence.  Centrica Plc (CNA)  : The stock was cut to
“underperform” from “neutral” at Bofa Merrill Lynch Global
Research. The stock slid 0.3 percent to 295.3 pence.  EnQuest Plc (ENQ)  : The North Sea oil company is in talks
with BP Plc to buy assets worth as much as 400 million pounds,
the Mail on Sunday reported, without saying where it got the
information. The shares gained 0.9 percent to 105.9 pence.  Essar Energy Plc (ESSR)  : The operator of  India ’s second-
biggest non-state crude oil refinery said first-half revenue
rose 37 percent. The company reported first-half pretax profit
of $278.5 million compared with $154.4 million. The shares
dropped 8.7 percent to 257.7 pence.  ICAP Plc (IAP)  : The interdealer broker will leave the
U.K. if the European Union endorses Franco-German plans for a
tax on financial transactions, the Independent on Sunday
reported, citing an interview with Chief Executive Officer
Michael Spencer. The stock rose 1.9 percent to 409.5 pence.  JD Sports Fashion Plc (JD/)  : The U.K.’s second-largest
sportswear chain hired commercial real estate brokers and
consultants Cushman & Wakefield to help the company open at
least 100 new stores in France, the Independent reported, citing
the group’s property director Nigel Keen. The shares climbed 6.5
percent to 874.5 pence.  Kingspan Group Plc (KSP)  : The company said the pace of
growth declined during the second quarter and “is likely to
ease further in the second half reflecting the limited evidence
to date of a sustained economic recovery in the group’s key
markets.” The company said first-half profit after tax rose 37
percent to 29.2 million euros from the year-earlier period. The
stock added 0.2 percent to 5.87 euros.  Lloyds Banking Group Plc (LLOY)  : Britain’s biggest
mortgage lender took all three confirmed bidders for the 632
branches it’s selling to the second round, the Sunday Telegraph
said, without saying where it got the information. The shares
dropped 4.8 percent to 28.38 pence.  Petrofac Plc (PFC LN): Chief Executive Officer Ayman Asfari
said the oil and gas engineer is on course to deliver like-for-
like net profit growth of at least 15 percent this year. The
stock jumped 3.1 percent to 1,168 pence.  Royal Dutch Shell Plc (RDSA)  :  Europe ’s largest oil
company said no oil has been released from the Gannet Alpha
platform off Scotland since divers closed the relief valve on
Aug. 19. The stock fell 2.4 percent to 1,883.5 pence.  SABMiller Plc (SAB)  : The brewer has spent as much as 120
million pounds ($198 million) buying Foster’s Group Ltd. shares
in recent days as part of a A$11.2 billion ($11.7 billion)
hostile bid for the Australian brewer, the Sunday Telegraph
said, without saying where it got the information. The shares
gained 0.3 percent to 2,015 pence.  Xstrata Plc (XTA)  : South Africa’s National Union of
Mineworkers says it’s in dispute with Xstrata over a share
ownership plan for employees, union spokesman Lesiba Seshoka
said. The stock dropped 2.1 percent to 951.7 pence.  To contact the reporters on this story:
